e imperialist message were once left-wing politically in Japan, where their work strongly favoured modernist, even avant-garde, styles of expression. In Glorify the Empire, Annika A. Culver explores how these once anti-imperialist intellectuals produced avant-garde works celebrating the modernity of a fascist state and reflecting a complicated picture of complicity with, and ambivalence toward, Japan's utopian project. Manchurian-themed cultural representations accelerated during the eruption of conflict with China, and later during the Second World War, when Manchukuo served as a template for Japanese-occupied areas in Southeast Asia. A groundbreaking work, Glorify the Empire magnifies the intersection between politics and art in a rarely examined period of Japanese history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArtistszJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aArtsxPolitical aspectszChinazManchuriaxHistoryy20th century. 0aAvant-garde (Aesthetics)xPolitical aspectszChinazManchuriaxHistoryy20th century. 0aPropaganda in art. 0aPropaganda, JapanesezChinazManchuriaxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945zChinazManchuriavArt and the war. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945zChinazManchuriaxPropaganda. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Propaganda.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013z978311127412608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013z978311127715808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077482438540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774824385423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774824385/original  a978-3-11-127412-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013b2013  a978-3-11-127715-8  ACUP Upgrade